T1  - Performance of Acquisitions of Distressed Firms
AU  - Bruton, Garry D.
AU  - Oviatt, Benjamin M.
AU  - White, Margaret A.
Y1  - 1994/08/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256607
DO  - 10.5465/256607
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 972
EP  - 989
VL  - 37
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In 51 acquisitions of financially distressed firms, related business combinations in which the acquirers had prior acquisition experience performed best. However, business relatedness and acquisition experience had no effect on performance in a control group of 46 acquisitions of firms that were not distressed. The results imply that tacit knowledge about the acquisition process and about how to integrate and manage the assets of distressed firms may be keys to their successful acquisition.
AB  - In 51 acquisitions of financially distressed firms, related business combinations in which the acquirers had prior acquisition experience performed best. However, business relatedness and acquisition experience had no effect on performance in a control group of 46 acquisitions of firms that were not distressed. The results imply that tacit knowledge about the acquisition process and about how to integrate and manage the assets of distressed firms may be keys to their successful acquisition.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256607
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256607
