T1  - Institutional Owners and Corporate Social Performance
AU  - Graves, Samuel B.
AU  - Waddock, Sandra A.
Y1  - 1994/08/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256611
DO  - 10.5465/256611
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1034
EP  - 1046
VL  - 37
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In this study, we hypothesize that institutions invest more heavily in companies with strong corporate social performance. Analysis indicated a significant, positive relationship between social performance and the number of institutions holding the shares of a company and a positive but insignificant relationship between social performance and the percentage of shares held by institutions. We conclude that improving a company's corporate social performance invokes no penalty in institutional ownership.
AB  - In this study, we hypothesize that institutions invest more heavily in companies with strong corporate social performance. Analysis indicated a significant, positive relationship between social performance and the number of institutions holding the shares of a company and a positive but insignificant relationship between social performance and the percentage of shares held by institutions. We conclude that improving a company's corporate social performance invokes no penalty in institutional ownership.
